00:09:30,102 --> 00:09:31,570
CARL: This had better work.

237
00:09:31,572 --> 00:09:34,172
Don't worry, Carl. Once
you save my dad's life,

238
00:09:34,174 --> 00:09:36,575
there's no way even he could
avoid thanking you for it.

239
00:09:36,577 --> 00:09:38,243
I hope for your
sake you're right.

240
00:09:38,844 --> 00:09:41,079
Y'know, it's funny
how no one's noticed

241
00:09:41,081 --> 00:09:44,449
a grand piano dangling
precariously over our table.

242
00:09:44,451 --> 00:09:46,785
Well, I also tied up a
couple of violins over there

243
00:09:46,787 --> 00:09:47,785
so it would seem
like a theme.

244
00:09:47,787 --> 00:09:50,088
All right, listen.
So when my dad returns,

245
00:09:50,090 --> 00:09:51,723
I'll excuse myself
and cut the rope

246
00:09:51,725 --> 00:09:54,759
and you push my dad out of the way
of the falling piano. Got it?

247
00:09:54,761 --> 00:09:56,628
Well, let's get to
that dessert menu.

248
00:09:56,630 --> 00:09:58,263
Excuse me, Dad.
It's my turn.

249
00:09:58,265 --> 00:09:59,864
I'll be right back.
You guys start.

250
00:09:59,866 --> 00:10:02,567
Sure, sure. Thank you
for not making us wait.

251
00:10:02,569 --> 00:10:04,869
(CHUCKLES) That bathroom
attendant was lovely.

252
00:10:04,871 --> 00:10:07,172
He gave me mints
and some floss.

253
00:10:07,174 --> 00:10:08,373
I just couldn't
thank him enough.

254
00:10:08,375 --> 00:10:09,741
(GASPS) Watch out, sir!

255
00:10:11,110 --> 00:10:13,411
Dad! Carl!
Are you all right?

256
00:10:13,413 --> 00:10:15,180
Oh, I'm fine.

257
00:10:15,548 --> 00:10:17,549
I'm all right too, sir.

258
00:10:17,551 --> 00:10:21,152
Wow, Carl. You saved
my dad's life.

259
00:10:21,154 --> 00:10:24,189
Yes. It's a shame he
couldn't save the table too.

260
00:10:24,191 --> 00:10:26,558
Let's go find the host. No, wait.
What? Seriously?

261
00:10:26,560 --> 00:10:27,859
What?
Dad.

262
00:10:28,227 --> 00:10:29,694
Aren't you going
to thank him?

263
00:10:29,696 --> 00:10:32,464
Oh, well, I didn't
realize, I hadn't.

264
00:10:32,466 --> 00:10:34,232
Thank you for pointing
that out to me, Monty.

265
00:10:34,234 --> 00:10:35,567
Dad!

266
00:10:35,569 --> 00:10:38,370
Oh, uh, yes, right.
Thank you, Carl.

267
00:10:40,606 --> 00:10:42,607
Oh, well, more
dessert for us.

268
00:10:43,175 --> 00:10:44,342
No, it's different
this time!

269
00:10:44,344 --> 00:10:46,144
She promised to come
down and meet us.

270
00:10:46,146 --> 00:10:48,613
Right. My expectations have
been completely reversed.

271
00:10:48,615 --> 00:10:50,815
No! You'll see. She'll
explain everything.

272
00:10:50,817 --> 00:10:51,916
Everything!

273
00:10:51,918 --> 00:10:53,284
(DOORBELL RINGS)

274
00:10:53,286 --> 00:10:54,552
(GIGGLES)

275
00:10:54,554 --> 00:10:56,321
(GASPS)
Yes! See.

276
00:10:56,323 --> 00:10:58,923
Mom, lady. Lady, Mom.
Now, tell her everything.

277
00:10:58,925 --> 00:11:00,925
You have the right to remain silent.
Anything you say...

278
00:11:00,927 --> 00:11:03,728
Take your hands off me, Copper!
I know my rights.

279
00:11:03,730 --> 00:11:06,564
Sorry, Candace. Water
the plant for me.

280
00:11:07,233 --> 00:11:08,867
I don't understand.
What's going on?

281
00:11:08,869 --> 00:11:09,667
Police matter, miss.

282
00:11:09,669 --> 00:11:12,904
What could that sweet old
lady have possibly done?

283
00:11:12,906 --> 00:11:15,840
That "sweet" old lady is
Peggy "The Pyramid" McGee,

284
00:11:15,842 --> 00:11:18,877
the notorious ringleader of
Danville's biggest pyramid scheme.

285
00:11:18,879 --> 00:11:19,577
Pyramid scheme?

286
00:11:19,579 --> 00:11:22,847
That's right. She's been
selling these all over town.

287
00:11:22,849 --> 00:11:25,850
See. These are just flat triangles
painted in perspective!

288
00:11:25,852 --> 00:11:26,550
That's fraud.

289
00:11:26,552 --> 00:11:30,588
I'll be out before the time
her mom serves pie!

290
00:11:31,424 --> 00:11:32,857
Wow, Candace.
I can't believe it.

291
00:11:32,859 --> 00:11:35,860
A pyramid scheme
right under our noses.

292
00:11:35,862 --> 00:11:37,929
Yeah.
Imagine that.

293
00:11:39,432 --> 00:11:40,965
(MELLOW MUSIC PLAYING)

294
00:11:42,401 --> 00:11:43,768
Hey!
Hey, yourself.

295
00:11:43,770 --> 00:11:44,836
I thought, uh...

296
00:11:44,838 --> 00:11:46,504
Yeah, so did I.

297
00:11:46,506 --> 00:11:49,641
But then I figured I couldn't
leave you here to suffer alone.

298
00:11:49,643 --> 00:11:50,341
That's what I like.

299
00:11:50,343 --> 00:11:52,844
Thoughtful and dismissive
simultaneously.

300
00:11:52,846 --> 00:11:56,281
DOOFENSHMIRTZ: (YELLS) No! Wait, wait, wait!
Is that the Love Sandals?

301
00:11:56,283 --> 00:12:00,418
Whoa! Watch the
hands, lady! Hey!

302
00:12:04,432 --> 00:12:07,801
Hey, Candace. Doing a little
light summer reading, I see.

303
00:12:07,803 --> 00:12:09,644
This is for the book club,
Jeremy and I joined.

304
00:12:09,738 --> 00:12:12,706
We all read the same book, and then
get together and discuss over tea.

305
00:12:12,708 --> 00:12:13,974
Sounds sophisticated.

306
00:12:13,976 --> 00:12:15,442
Yeah, the tea
was my idea.

307
00:12:15,444 --> 00:12:17,411
This week we're
reading, <i>The Iliad.</i>

308
00:12:17,413 --> 00:12:18,545
That's a great book!

309
00:12:18,547 --> 00:12:20,447
It's all about
the Trojan War!

310
00:12:20,682 --> 00:12:22,316
You read this?
BUFORD: We all did.

311
00:12:22,318 --> 00:12:23,984
You're not the only one
with a book club, you know.

312
00:12:23,986 --> 00:12:25,786
I like your idea
about the tea, though.

313
00:12:25,788 --> 00:12:26,786
Ferb, make
a note of that.

314
00:12:26,788 --> 00:12:29,890
The war started because Paris
fell in love with Helen of Troy.

315
00:12:29,892 --> 00:12:30,690
It's so romantic.

316
00:12:30,692 --> 00:12:34,962
Yeah, and Helen could launch a
thousand ships with her face!

317
00:12:34,964 --> 00:12:36,597
My favorite character
was Achilles,

318
00:12:36,599 --> 00:12:38,832
the greatest Greek
warrior of all time.

319
00:12:38,834 --> 00:12:40,601
He had this big
fight with Hector.

320
00:12:40,603 --> 00:12:42,436
He was all,
wham! Bam!

321
00:12:42,438 --> 00:12:43,737
Stab! Stab! Stab!
Cut it out!

322
00:12:43,739 --> 00:12:45,706
Isn't there something
about a wooden horse?

323
00:12:45,708 --> 00:12:48,609
Yeah, the Greek army built
a huge wooden horse

324
00:12:48,611 --> 00:12:50,911
and left it outside
the gates of Troy.

325
00:12:50,913 --> 00:12:53,280
<i>The Trojans thought that</i>
<i>the Greeks had given up</i>

326
00:12:53,282 --> 00:12:55,549
<i>and that the horse was</i>
<i>some sort of tribute to them.</i>

327
00:12:55,551 --> 00:12:56,549
So, they wheeled
it inside the gates.

328
00:12:56,551 --> 00:13:00,420
Hey. How did they get that
big horse in that tiny door?

329
00:13:00,422 --> 00:13:02,890
Buford, just try
imaging a larger door.

330
00:13:02,892 --> 00:13:04,458
Oh, okay. Hang on.

331
00:13:05,693 --> 00:13:06,492
Oh, yeah.
That's better.

332
00:13:06,494 --> 00:13:09,596
Then late at night, the Greeks climbed
out of the horse, opened the gates...

333
00:13:09,598 --> 00:13:11,832
Then it was all, wham,
zam, stab, stab, stab.

334
00:13:11,834 --> 00:13:12,900
Cut it out!

335
00:13:12,902 --> 00:13:14,701
Wow, really
sounds exciting.

336
00:13:14,703 --> 00:13:15,401
I better
get started.

337
00:13:15,403 --> 00:13:17,938
Book club is in
three hours. Bye!

338
00:13:17,940 --> 00:13:20,073
Wow. She must
be a fast reader.

339
00:13:20,475 --> 00:13:21,608
What gets me is,

340
00:13:21,610 --> 00:13:23,477
